1
00:01:38,466 --> 00:01:39,128
Pyne.

2
00:01:45,224 --> 00:01:46,241
What is it, sir?

3
00:01:49,894 --> 00:01:50,516
Oh.

4
00:01:51,622 --> 00:01:53,650
Why, it's Mr Robin, sir.

5
00:01:54,350 --> 00:01:55,012
Pyne.

6
00:01:55,383 --> 00:01:58,490
Young Sperling was here with him
this morning. See if he's still around.

7
00:01:59,016 --> 00:02:00,808
While I will call the district attorney.

8
00:02:01,360 --> 00:02:02,151
Yes, sir.

9
00:02:15,025 --> 00:02:17,671
Good morning, professor.
How are you this beautiful morning?

10
00:02:18,007 --> 00:02:19,393
A terrible thing has happened.

11
00:02:19,595 --> 00:02:21,258
A young man, a friend of my niece's.

12
00:02:21,909 --> 00:02:23,363
Has been murdered at my house.

13
00:02:23,649 --> 00:02:25,183
Try to calm yourself, professor.

14
00:02:25,668 --> 00:02:27,363
I'll get Philo Vance on this at once.

15
00:02:28,003 --> 00:02:30,792
In the meantime, give me all the
details you can over the phone.

16
00:02:31,221 --> 00:02:32,489
In the first place.

17
00:02:37,125 --> 00:02:38,200
Mr Markham, sir.

18
00:02:38,670 --> 00:02:40,374
It seems urgent.
Will you speak to him?

19
00:02:40,576 --> 00:02:41,399
Certainly.

20
00:02:45,903 --> 00:02:47,562
I say, old fellow. Don't you ever sleep?

21
00:02:47,764 --> 00:02:49,524
There's been a murder committed, Philo.

22
00:02:50,174 --> 00:02:51,641
At the home of Professor Dillard.

23
00:02:51,922 --> 00:02:53,004
Professor Dillard?

24
00:02:54,293 --> 00:02:56,207
That interests me, Markham. Read on.

25
00:02:56,839 --> 00:02:57,996
A man named Robin.

26
00:02:58,684 --> 00:03:00,218
Was killed with a bow and arrow.

27
00:03:01,340 --> 00:03:02,034
Robin?

28
00:03:02,853 --> 00:03:04,032
Killed with an arrow?

29
00:03:05,297 --> 00:03:08,133
My dear fellow, confess. You've been
on a wild chase with mother goose.

30
00:03:08,517 --> 00:03:09,847
No. That's the story.

31
00:03:10,205 --> 00:03:11,863
A fairytale in terms of blood, eh?

32
00:03:13,181 --> 00:03:14,230
Alright, Markham.

33
00:03:15,269 --> 00:03:16,932
I'll meet you there in half an hour.

34
00:03:20,540 --> 00:03:21,808
Dark suit. Dark hat.

35
00:03:22,559 --> 00:03:23,350
Dark tie.

36
00:03:24,057 --> 00:03:26,142
And bring me some more hot coffee.

37
00:03:26,626 --> 00:03:28,317
Very good, sir.
- Yarma.

38
00:03:29,499 --> 00:03:31,969
Look on my reference
shelf and bring me ..

39
00:03:33,137 --> 00:03:34,738
Dr. Elmer's book on archery.

40
00:03:36,225 --> 00:03:37,503
The home book of verse.

41
00:03:38,333 --> 00:03:39,613
And the German dictionary.

42
00:03:39,815 --> 00:03:40,800
Very good, sir.

43
00:03:59,694 --> 00:04:01,166
What do you know of this, officer?

44
00:04:01,368 --> 00:04:03,774
The body is in the yard, sir.
Sergeant Heath is in charge.

45
00:04:04,092 --> 00:04:05,932
Says he has the case
practically solved, sir.

46
00:04:06,134 --> 00:04:07,119
Come on, Vance.

47
00:04:14,425 --> 00:04:16,476
He converted this garden
into an archery range.

48
00:04:17,174 --> 00:04:19,176
Miss Dillard is quite distressed.

49
00:04:22,888 --> 00:04:24,422
Morning, Heath.
- Morning, sir.

50
00:04:24,689 --> 00:04:26,472
Hello Mr Vance. Good to see you, sir.

51
00:04:27,332 --> 00:04:30,480
Sorry they troubled you, Mr Markham.
It's an open and shut case.

52
00:04:31,045 --> 00:04:33,111
I have it practically solved right now.

53
00:04:33,602 --> 00:04:34,748
First degree murder.

54
00:04:35,646 --> 00:04:37,018
How nice for you, Sergeant.

55
00:04:37,242 --> 00:04:40,093
As long as I'm here you don't mind
if I take a little look around?

56
00:04:40,672 --> 00:04:42,992
No. Go as far as you like.
- Thank you, Sergeant.

57
00:04:43,918 --> 00:04:45,534
See here, Mr Markham.

58
00:04:52,029 --> 00:04:53,528
Sergeant.
- Yes, Mr Vance?

59
00:04:54,118 --> 00:04:55,788
How about the bow that fired this arrow?

60
00:04:56,258 --> 00:04:58,286
Well, that was our one best bet.

61
00:04:58,803 --> 00:05:01,259
But one of the servants
picked it up in the alley here.

62
00:05:01,742 --> 00:05:04,388
Carried it into the archery room
and gummed up the fingerprints.

63
00:05:04,754 --> 00:05:06,353
What have you done about Sperling?

64
00:05:06,586 --> 00:05:07,797
We've got his address.

65
00:05:08,220 --> 00:05:09,625
He lives up Westchester way.

66
00:05:09,930 --> 00:05:12,305
Two of my men are bringing him here now.
- Very good.

67
00:05:12,897 --> 00:05:13,655
Officer.

68
00:05:15,725 --> 00:05:18,316
Mind demonstrating a point for us?
- Not at all, sir.

69
00:05:19,150 --> 00:05:20,536
When I touch you with my stick.

70
00:05:20,738 --> 00:05:22,337
I want you to fall over backwards.

71
00:05:22,640 --> 00:05:24,569
As if you'd been hit in
the heart with an arrow.

72
00:05:24,771 --> 00:05:26,922
Yes, sir.
- Stand where you are.

73
00:05:27,389 --> 00:05:28,545
Thank you. Ready?

74
00:05:34,122 --> 00:05:34,913
Sergeant.

75
00:05:38,331 --> 00:05:40,449
You will notice that the
first instinct of a man.

76
00:05:41,001 --> 00:05:42,212
Shot in a vital organ.

77
00:05:42,650 --> 00:05:45,834
Is to draw in his arms
towards the wound.

78
00:05:47,498 --> 00:05:48,289
His legs.

79
00:05:48,977 --> 00:05:49,962
Are doubled up.

80
00:05:51,140 --> 00:05:52,319
You will also notice.

81
00:05:53,128 --> 00:05:55,389
That his hat has fallen at his head.

82
00:05:56,486 --> 00:05:57,410
Now, Sergeant.

83
00:05:58,613 --> 00:05:59,859
In Robin's case.

84
00:06:00,842 --> 00:06:03,440
The arms and legs are straightened out.

85
00:06:04,237 --> 00:06:05,221
And his hat.

86
00:06:06,439 --> 00:06:07,864
Not only lies at his feet.

87
00:06:08,629 --> 00:06:10,583
But is a good foot and
a half away from him.

88
00:06:13,120 --> 00:06:15,139
Alright, officer. That will be all.
Thank you.

89
00:06:16,316 --> 00:06:18,234
We're wasting our time, Mr Markham.

90
00:06:18,663 --> 00:06:20,423
What is the good of all these theories?

91
00:06:21,442 --> 00:06:22,847
Sperling is the boy we want.

92
00:06:23,271 --> 00:06:25,857
And when my men bring him
in the case will be closed.

93
00:06:27,292 --> 00:06:30,661
Sperling was probably in
love with the Dillard girl.

94
00:06:31,388 --> 00:06:32,599
Had a chat with Robin.

95
00:06:32,992 --> 00:06:35,405
Grabbed a bow and arrow.
Followed Robin outside.

96
00:06:35,728 --> 00:06:37,551
Shoots him through
the heart and beats it.

97
00:06:37,753 --> 00:06:38,544
Sergeant.

98
00:06:39,180 --> 00:06:41,458
You are much too trusting
for this deceitful world.

99
00:06:41,867 --> 00:06:43,726
If everything happened
as neatly as that.

100
00:06:44,138 --> 00:06:45,524
Life would be very simple.

101
00:06:45,939 --> 00:06:47,407
And .. very dull.

102
00:06:47,958 --> 00:06:49,815
Yes. But Philo.
- Wait a minute, Markham.

103
00:06:51,523 --> 00:06:52,798
Don't ignore the fact ..

104
00:06:53,731 --> 00:06:56,101
That Robin was facing
the arrow and therefore ..

105
00:06:56,781 --> 00:06:58,476
Would have had time to cover himself.

106
00:07:00,239 --> 00:07:00,997
By Jove.

107
00:07:02,117 --> 00:07:03,457
I've overlooked something.

108
00:07:03,700 --> 00:07:06,785
If a man is stabbed in the heart there's
sure to be an immediate flow of blood.

109
00:07:07,157 --> 00:07:08,053
Especially.

110
00:07:08,501 --> 00:07:10,926
When the tip of the weapon
is larger than the shaft.

111
00:07:11,460 --> 00:07:13,094
Yes. That is so.
- It is ..

112
00:07:13,751 --> 00:07:16,569
Quite possible, Sergeant, you
will find some blood spots.

113
00:07:17,074 --> 00:07:18,285
On the floor of the ..

114
00:07:18,920 --> 00:07:20,080
The archery room.

115
00:07:20,379 --> 00:07:21,622
Look and see, will you?

116
00:07:25,473 --> 00:07:26,490
See here, Vance.

117
00:07:27,108 --> 00:07:28,287
What is in your mind?

118
00:07:29,420 --> 00:07:30,535
Numberless things.

119
00:07:32,585 --> 00:07:36,625
They boil down to the notion that Robin
wasn't killed by a bow and arrow at all.

120
00:07:37,044 --> 00:07:39,544
Hang it all, Mr Vance.
You had the dope alright.

121
00:07:40,089 --> 00:07:42,014
There is a dark stain
on the cement floor.

122
00:07:42,440 --> 00:07:44,606
The coroner here says it is human blood.

123
00:07:44,808 --> 00:07:46,213
Morning, doctor.
- Morning.

124
00:07:46,430 --> 00:07:48,739
You fellows must have an
arrangement with these people.

125
00:07:49,056 --> 00:07:51,745
Every time I have a day off they
go and get themselves murdered.

126
00:07:52,596 --> 00:07:55,401
And a nice fancy murder you've
picked out for me this time.

127
00:07:59,024 --> 00:08:00,779
If I were you, doctor, I should ..

128
00:08:01,650 --> 00:08:04,914
I should examine the base
of the skull for a bad fracture.

129
00:08:09,055 --> 00:08:10,654
Your suspicions were right, Vance.

130
00:08:11,348 --> 00:08:13,535
The skull is fractured, and badly too.

131
00:08:14,087 --> 00:08:15,920
It looks like he had a crushing blow.

132
00:08:16,212 --> 00:08:19,038
The professor and his niece are ready
for you in the archery room, sir.

133
00:08:19,273 --> 00:08:21,356
Alright, Sergeant. You're in charge.
- Yes, sir.

134
00:08:24,150 --> 00:08:25,199
Sergeant.
- Sir?

135
00:08:25,443 --> 00:08:27,203
Just because this case looks so simple.

136
00:08:27,526 --> 00:08:30,712
I trust you have not neglected to take
your usual excellent photographs?

137
00:08:31,025 --> 00:08:32,139
Certainly not, sir.

138
00:08:32,377 --> 00:08:34,783
They are being developed right now.
- Thank you, Sergeant.

139
00:08:36,108 --> 00:08:38,902
Come on. What's the matter with you?
Get busy and take these pictures.

140
00:08:39,359 --> 00:08:41,938
What's the idea? You just spending
the day here or something?

141
00:08:57,250 --> 00:08:59,277
Good morning, professor.
- Good morning.

142
00:09:00,027 --> 00:09:02,624
I regret that a tragedy should
be the reason for this meeting.

143
00:09:03,288 --> 00:09:05,477
You remember my niece, don't you?
- Yes indeed.

144
00:09:06,267 --> 00:09:08,027
I want you both to meet Mr Philo Vance.

145
00:09:08,569 --> 00:09:09,658
How do you do, sir?

146
00:09:09,860 --> 00:09:12,008
If you tell him just what
you know of the tragedy.

147
00:09:12,456 --> 00:09:13,815
He'll be of great help to us.

148
00:09:14,017 --> 00:09:15,939
Won't you sit down, gentlemen?
- Thank you.

149
00:09:16,214 --> 00:09:17,619
You sit down there, my dear.

150
00:09:25,111 --> 00:09:28,404
I told Markham practically everything
that I knew over the telephone.

151
00:09:30,239 --> 00:09:33,677
Robin and Sperling called to see Belle.
But she was out playing tennis.

152
00:09:36,165 --> 00:09:38,505
I heard them talking up in the
drawing room for a few minutes.

153
00:09:39,518 --> 00:09:41,128
Then they came on down here.

154
00:09:42,392 --> 00:09:44,152
I worked in my study for about an hour.

155
00:09:45,236 --> 00:09:46,943
And I thought I heard a noise.

156
00:09:47,902 --> 00:09:49,210
It sounded like a scream.

157
00:09:49,914 --> 00:09:51,480
But I couldn't be sure because ..

158
00:09:52,017 --> 00:09:53,906
The maid was using the
vacuum in the hall.

159
00:09:54,778 --> 00:09:55,440
Then.

160
00:09:57,023 --> 00:09:58,410
I stepped out onto the balcony.

161
00:10:00,027 --> 00:10:01,238
And saw the body of ..

162
00:10:02,092 --> 00:10:02,947
Poor Robin.

163
00:10:06,014 --> 00:10:07,096
The rest you know.

164
00:10:09,067 --> 00:10:10,022
About that ..

165
00:10:10,932 --> 00:10:12,014
Scream, professor.

166
00:10:13,164 --> 00:10:16,093
Could you be at all sure from
what direction it came?

167
00:10:17,055 --> 00:10:17,652
No.

168
00:10:18,559 --> 00:10:20,836
I could not be sure that it
was a scream that I heard.

169
00:10:21,528 --> 00:10:24,179
It might have been an automobile siren.

170
00:10:24,873 --> 00:10:27,092
We hear so many traffic
noises from the drive.

171
00:10:27,693 --> 00:10:30,584
Where were the other members of your
household at the time of the murder?

172
00:10:32,213 --> 00:10:33,618
The cook had gone to market.

173
00:10:33,852 --> 00:10:35,289
Belle was out playing tennis.

174
00:10:37,737 --> 00:10:38,687
Mr Arnesson.

175
00:10:39,240 --> 00:10:42,138
My adopted son, had left
for the university.

176
00:10:43,285 --> 00:10:45,246
We phoned to him but he wasn't there.

177
00:10:45,805 --> 00:10:48,845
So we left him a message. I do hope
they've been able to find him by now.

178
00:10:49,377 --> 00:10:50,075
I see.

179
00:10:53,866 --> 00:10:54,560
I say.

180
00:10:56,389 --> 00:10:58,030
There is an arrow missing here.

181
00:10:58,514 --> 00:10:59,531
That is strange.

182
00:11:00,076 --> 00:11:01,771
It has been taken in great haste too.

183
00:11:03,745 --> 00:11:04,683
This holder.

184
00:11:05,754 --> 00:11:06,804
Has been badly ..

185
00:11:07,409 --> 00:11:08,071
Bent.

186
00:11:08,692 --> 00:11:09,896
Poor cock robin.

187
00:11:14,304 --> 00:11:15,159
Cock robin?

188
00:11:17,045 --> 00:11:18,288
We all called him that.

189
00:11:19,233 --> 00:11:21,062
We did it to tease him.

190
00:11:22,004 --> 00:11:22,924
Miss Dillard.

191
00:11:23,253 --> 00:11:26,284
Did you happen to know by any chance
that Sperling in German means ..

192
00:11:26,847 --> 00:11:27,605
Sparrow?

193
00:11:29,369 --> 00:11:29,998
Yes.

194
00:11:30,319 --> 00:11:31,209
Yes I know.

195
00:11:31,670 --> 00:11:32,719
You speak German?

196
00:11:33,138 --> 00:11:33,775
No.

197
00:11:34,171 --> 00:11:36,347
Then how did you know that
Sperling means sparrow?

198
00:11:37,232 --> 00:11:37,894
Well.

199
00:11:38,672 --> 00:11:39,624
The other day.

200
00:11:39,911 --> 00:11:42,163
Robin stepped out
onto the archery range.

201
00:11:42,682 --> 00:11:44,809
Just as Mr Sperling aimed at the target.

202
00:11:45,660 --> 00:11:48,218
Mr Arnesson was watching
and called to Robin.

203
00:11:48,899 --> 00:11:49,819
'Be careful'.

204
00:11:50,442 --> 00:11:53,357
You are a cock robin in
that archer is a sparrow.

205
00:11:57,926 --> 00:12:00,494
Mr Arnesson seems very well
acquainted with his nursery rhymes.

206
00:12:04,845 --> 00:12:06,841
Just a minute.
Where do you think you're going?

207
00:12:07,043 --> 00:12:09,355
I am Eric Arnesson. I live here.
I was telephoned for.

208
00:12:09,984 --> 00:12:12,649
Of course, if you don't want me
to come in that's alright with me.

209
00:12:12,857 --> 00:12:15,708
Sorry. I didn't know who you were.
- Why is the house littered with police?

210
00:12:15,910 --> 00:12:17,556
Who at best are hardly ornamental.

211
00:12:17,940 --> 00:12:19,842
There has been a murder, sir.
A young man.

212
00:12:20,513 --> 00:12:22,902
They are expecting you so
you'll get the details inside.

213
00:12:23,367 --> 00:12:24,978
A murder?
- Come on, Johnny.

214
00:12:28,525 --> 00:12:31,018
Mama, I want to go home
because I'm hungry.

215
00:12:31,358 --> 00:12:32,638
Hush dear. Mother is busy.

216
00:12:33,371 --> 00:12:34,970
There is Mr Arnesson now.
- Eric.

217
00:12:35,307 --> 00:12:35,969
Eric.

218
00:12:36,434 --> 00:12:37,886
I am so glad you're here.

219
00:12:38,527 --> 00:12:40,883
Robin has been killed.
- Robin?

220
00:12:41,561 --> 00:12:42,416
Cock robin.

221
00:12:43,976 --> 00:12:46,682
His name was against him, wasn't it?
- Please don't.

222
00:12:47,213 --> 00:12:48,691
Don't be cynical now.

223
00:12:49,260 --> 00:12:50,972
For my sake.
- I am sorry, darling.

224
00:12:51,347 --> 00:12:52,337
And Johnny's.

225
00:12:53,234 --> 00:12:55,860
I know how hard this is for you, Johnny.

226
00:12:56,338 --> 00:12:58,512
What great pals you and Robin were.

227
00:13:00,506 --> 00:13:01,872
I can't believe it.

228
00:13:03,359 --> 00:13:04,699
Hello Markham.
- Morning.

229
00:13:04,954 --> 00:13:05,912
Morning, doctor.

230
00:13:06,114 --> 00:13:07,357
Mr Vance - Mr Arnesson.

231
00:13:07,568 --> 00:13:08,520
How do you do?

232
00:13:08,744 --> 00:13:10,913
This is John Sprigg, one of my students.
- Yes.

233
00:13:11,372 --> 00:13:13,777
Robin was the best friend
I had in the world.

234
00:13:16,819 --> 00:13:18,992
And I'm going to find
the man who murdered him.

235
00:13:22,055 --> 00:13:25,001
Taking death tragically is
one of the weaknesses of youth.

236
00:13:26,194 --> 00:13:28,255
So we have a real murder
mystery, have we?

237
00:13:28,819 --> 00:13:30,921
Might I be entrusted with the details?

238
00:13:31,503 --> 00:13:33,561
Where were Robin and
Sperling when you left?

239
00:13:34,266 --> 00:13:35,768
Downstairs in the archery room.

240
00:13:36,787 --> 00:13:37,922
Is that so?

241
00:13:40,161 --> 00:13:42,306
Did you overhear anything they said?

242
00:13:42,859 --> 00:13:44,696
I don't listen at keyholes.

243
00:13:46,120 --> 00:13:48,224
Well, little bright-eyes.

244
00:13:49,287 --> 00:13:52,834
They ought to erect a statue to you
for being the first woman who don't.

245
00:13:54,768 --> 00:13:56,789
Was there anybody else
in the archery room?

246
00:13:57,237 --> 00:13:58,609
When you left this morning.

247
00:13:59,352 --> 00:14:00,884
I thought I heard Mr Drukker.

248
00:14:02,331 --> 00:14:05,286
But he sneaks in and out at
all hours of the day and night.

249
00:14:07,922 --> 00:14:10,338
Now we are getting somewhere.

250
00:14:11,494 --> 00:14:15,662
You can tell me all about this case and
let me work it out on scientific lines.

251
00:14:15,994 --> 00:14:17,017
Is that a bargain?

252
00:14:17,219 --> 00:14:19,910
Of course, we can't very well
promise to tell everything we know.

253
00:14:20,458 --> 00:14:22,283
It might be indiscreet.
- Wait a minute.

254
00:14:22,898 --> 00:14:25,240
Wait a minute, Markham.
I really don't see any reason ..

